0:{"rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[[["$","nav",null,{"children":[["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/","className":"logo","children":["EV",["$","span",null,{"children":"TIMES"}]]}],["$","ul",null,{"className":"nav-links","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"#","children":"Vehicles"}]}],["$","li",null,{"children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"#","children":"Charging"}]}],["$","li",null,{"children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"#","children":"Policy"}]}],["$","li",null,{"children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"#","children":"Battery Tech"}]}],["$","li",null,{"children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"#","children":"Startups"}]}],["$","li",null,{"children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"#","children":"Market"}]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"nav-right","children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/login","className":"btn-ghost","children":"login"}]}]]}],["$","main",null,{"className":"article-page","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"article-shell","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/","className":"article-back","children":"← Back to homepage"}],["$","article",null,{"className":"article-detail","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"article-kicker","children":"Policy · Analysis"}],["$","h1",null,{"children":"India's FAME III subsidy scheme could reshape the EV market — here's what we know"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"article-standfirst","children":"The government is expected to announce a revised subsidy structure that extends support to private four-wheelers for the first time, potentially unlocking demand from a segment that has remained price-sensitive."}],["$","div",null,{"className":"article-byline","children":[["$","span",null,{"children":"Priya Mehta"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"•"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"6 min read"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"•"}],["$","span",null,{"children":"2 hours ago"}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"article-body","children":[["$","p","India's expected FAME III framework is shaping up to be more ambitious than earlier EV incentive rounds. Officials are reportedly focusing on a broader adoption curve instead of limiting support to narrow use-cases.",{"children":"India's expected FAME III framework is shaping up to be more ambitious than earlier EV incentive rounds. Officials are reportedly focusing on a broader adoption curve instead of limiting support to narrow use-cases."}],["$","p","The biggest shift could be support for private four-wheelers, a category that has struggled to break into the mainstream because of upfront cost. If that arrives, it would materially improve affordability for urban families considering their first EV.",{"children":"The biggest shift could be support for private four-wheelers, a category that has struggled to break into the mainstream because of upfront cost. If that arrives, it would materially improve affordability for urban families considering their first EV."}],["$","p","Automakers, charging providers, and battery suppliers would all feel the impact. Companies with local manufacturing and strong entry-level products are likely to benefit first, while premium players may gain later through demand spillover.",{"children":"Automakers, charging providers, and battery suppliers would all feel the impact. Companies with local manufacturing and strong entry-level products are likely to benefit first, while premium players may gain later through demand spillover."}],["$","p","The open question is execution. Incentives alone will not solve charging access, financing friction, or resale uncertainty, but a credible long-term policy could still change the pace of India's EV transition.",{"children":"The open question is execution. Incentives alone will not solve charging access, financing friction, or resale uncertainty, but a credible long-term policy could still change the pace of India's EV transition."}]]}]]}]]}]}],[["$","div",null,{"className":"footer-top","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"footer-brand","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"logo